# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vitamin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] Natural vitamin K is a derivative of 1,4-naphthoquinone.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] It is a planar molecule with one aromatic ring fused to a quinone subunit.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] 1,4-naphathoquinone itself has some vitamin K activity.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] However, naphthoquinone rapidly oxidizes to phthalic anhydride under these conditions, and the latter is the major product.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] In the laboratory, naphthoquinone can be produced by the oxidation of a variety of naphthalene compounds.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] An inexpensive route involves oxidation of naphthalene with chromium trioxide.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] 1,4-Naphthoquinone acts as strong dienophile in Diels-Alder reaction.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] Reduction of 1,4-naphthoquinone with dithionite gives 1,4-dihydroxynaphthalene.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] The reaction is reversible: oxidation of the diol give back the quinone.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] 1,4-Naphthoquinone is mainly used as a precursor to anthraquinone by reaction with butadiene followed by oxidation.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] Nitration gives 5-nitro-1,4-naphthalenedione, precursor to an aminoanthroquinone that is used as a dye precursor.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] Naphthoquinone functions as a ligand through its electrophilic carbon-carbon double bonds.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] Naphthoquinone forms the central chemical structure of many natural compounds, most notably the K vitamins.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] 2-Methyl-1,4-naphthoquinone, called menadione, is a more effective coagulant than vitamin K.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] Some naphthoquinone derivatives are cytotoxic, they have significant antibacterial, antifungal, antiviral, insecticidal, anti-inflammatory, and antipyretic properties.
[src:vitamin/1-4-naphthoquinone] Plants with naphthoquinone content are widely used in China and the countries of South America, where they are used to treat malignant and parasitic diseases.
[src:vitamin/2-methylnaphthalene-1-4-diamine] 2-Methylnaphthalene-1,4-diamine was first synthesized in 1925.
[src:vitamin/2-methylnaphthalene-1-4-diamine] In 1942 two different research groups noted the vitamin K activity of the compound.
[src:vitamin/2-methylnaphthalene-1-4-diamine] It forms a dihydrochloride salt (C11H14Cl2N2) with hydrochloric acid and one of the aforementioned research groups suggested the name **vitamin K6** for the salt.
[src:vitamin/2-methylnaphthalene-1-4-diamine] 2-Methylnaphthalene-1,4-diamine and its dihydrochloride can be made from 2-methylnaphthalene or its close analogs.
[src:vitamin/2-methylnaphthalene-1-4-diamine] Dihydrochloride blackens without melting at about 300 °C.
[src:vitamin/2-methylnaphthalene-1-4-diamine] 4-Amino-3-methyl-1-naphthol or its dihydrochloride have not been used as commercial medicinal forms of vitamin K unlike phylloquinone and menadione for example.
[src:vitamin/2-methylnaphthalene-1-4-diamine] Oral toxicity of dihydrochloride for rats is approximately the same as for 4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol hydrochloride.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] Vitamin K function of the compound was first noted in 1940.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] Oral lethal dose for the HCl salt in rats is 0.7 g/kg.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] 4-Amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol HCl salt is a vitamin K and prevents bleeding caused by vitamin K deficiency when given via intravenous or intramuscular injections at doses of about 1–3 mg.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] HCl salt is water-soluble and its parenteral administration requires no emulsifiers unlike fat-soluble phylloquinone for example, which is often in formulations with lecithin or glycocholic acid.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] Parenterally given 1 mg/ml aqueous solutions and orally taken 4 mg tablets of the HCl salt have been available commercially.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] 4-Amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol HCl salt has a mass of 209.57 g/mol.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] It darkens at 262 °C and decays without melting at 280–282 °C.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] HCl salt breaks down in aqueous solutions via oxidation which is quite fast at neutral pH.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] First a pink and later a purple precipitant forms.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] The colored precipitant is (4-oxy-2-methylnaphtylimine)-2-methyl-1,4-naphthoquinone, which is a condensation reaction product of 4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol and menadione.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] Latter is formed via oxidation and deamination of 4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] 4-Amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol can be made from 2-methylnaphthalene or menadione.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] 4-Amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol HCl salt prevents the growth of different molds and bacteria.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] Thus it has been studied as potential food preservative.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-2-methyl-1-naphthol] HCl salt has been studied as a potential treatment for cancer as it prevents glycolysis in cancer cells, which provides them energy for growth.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-3-methyl-1-naphthol] It can be made from 2-methylnaphthalene or menadione.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-3-methyl-1-naphthol] It forms a crystalline hydrochloride salt (C11H11NO·HCl) from hydrochloric acid.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-3-methyl-1-naphthol] At least 1 g of the salt dissolves in 25 ml of water at 75 °C.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-3-methyl-1-naphthol] The salt turns pink to dark violet on exposure to air and light.
[src:vitamin/4-amino-3-methyl-1-naphthol] 4-Amino-3-methyl-1-naphthol or its hydrochloride have not been used as commercial medicinal forms of vitamin K unlike phylloquinone and menadione for example.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Food sources of PABA include liver, brewer's yeast (and unfiltered beer), kidney, molasses, mushrooms, and whole grains.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Other food sources of PABA include spinach and oat seeds.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is an intermediate in the synthesis of folate by bacteria, plants, and fungi.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Many bacteria, including those found in the human intestinal tract such as *E. coli*, generate PABA from chorismate by the combined action of the enzymes 4-amino-4-deoxychorismate synthase and 4-amino-4-deoxychorismate lyase.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Plants produce PABA in their chloroplasts, and store it as a glucose ester (*p*ABA-Glc) in their tissues.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The malarial protozoan *Plasmodium* only make PABA when necessary, preferring to get it from the surroundings if able to.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Some bacteria, including a few found in the human microbiome, are unable to make PABA for themselves but can use PABA to make folate.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] A few are very efficient at the PABA-to-folate conversion despite not making their own PABA.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Sulfonamide drugs are structurally similar to PABA, and their antibacterial activity is due to their ability to interfere with the conversion of PABA to folate by the enzyme dihydropteroate synthetase.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Thus, bacterial growth is limited through folate deficiency.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA has been referred to historically as "vitamin Bx", but plays no direct role in animal cells and is hence no longer recognized as a vitamin.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Animals (including humans) are unable to use PABA in any way and so require folate from dietary sources such as green leafy vegetables.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA can play a role in the supply of folate to an animal via its microbiome; this is best demonstrated in the worm *C. elegans*, in which addition of PABA could increase folate production by resident *E. coli* and correct for deficiencies.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The *C. elegans* folate transporter only works with the reduced form (tetrahydrofolate, THF and derivatives such as folinic acid), not regular folic acid.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Any folic acid from the environment is only usable following spontaneous breakdown to PABA-glu, which *E. coli* uses to make THF.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In contrast, humans can directly use oxidized folates thanks to the proton-coupled folate transporter and have no need for this detour; this "recycling" of PABA-glu would, at best, compensate for folate degredation.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The above do not seem to apply in normal mammals, however.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Despite detection of gut-produced folate being incorporated into mammals, *ex vivo* folate synthesis capacity of fecal bacteria have no correlation with the folate status of their donors.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Furthermore, comparison with germ-free animals show that under a chow diet, the mouse microbiome is a net consumer of folate.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The caveat is that the mouse chow is more folate-rich than typical human diets and may be encouraging a shift towards a folate-consuming microbiome.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] There are no reports of any usefulness of PABA in germ-free animals.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA and its salts are used in nutritional epidemiological studies to assess the completeness of 24-hour urine collection for the determination of urinary sodium, potassium, or nitrogen levels.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The potassium salt (potassium paraaminobenzoate, "aminobenzoate potassium") is used as a drug against fibrotic skin disorders, such as Peyronie's disease, under the brand name Potaba.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] It is believed to work by inhibiting fibroblast glycosaminoglycan secretion and stabilizing monoamine oxidase A activity.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is also occasionally used in pill form by sufferers of irritable bowel syndrome to treat its associated gastrointestinal symptoms.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA derivatives have also been proposed to function as acetylcholinesterase inhibitors in diseases that cause deficient cholinergic systems, such as Alzheimer's Disease.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Despite the lack of any recognized syndromes of PABA deficiency in humans, except for those who lack the colonic bacteria that generate PABA, many claims of benefit are made by commercial suppliers of PABA as a nutritional supplement.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The benefit is claimed for fatigue, irritability, depression, weeping eczema (moist eczema), scleroderma (premature hardening of the skin), patchy pigment loss in the skin (vitiligo), and premature grey hair.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA finds use in the biomedical sector.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Its derivatives are found as a structural component in 1.5% of a database of 12111 commercial drugs.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Other uses include its conversion to specialty azo dyes and crosslinking agents.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is also used as a biodegradable pesticide, though its use is now limited due to evolution of new variants of bio-pesticides.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Specifically, studies have shown that PABA photodegrades through an O2-mediated pathway in which PABA is oxidized by O2 via hydrogen abstraction and decarboxylation.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In the past, PABA was widely used in sunscreens as a UV filter.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] It is a UVB absorber, meaning it can absorb wavelengths between 290 and 320 nm. while still allowing UVA wavelengths between 320-400 nm to pass through, producing a tan.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The chemical structure of PABA, with the amino and carboxyl groups being *para* to each other, allows for easy electron delocalization, which reduces the gap between the highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) and lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO).
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] This makes it easier for the electrons in PABA to transition to a higher energy state upon absorbing light.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Patented in 1943, PABA was one of the first active ingredients to be used in sunscreen.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The first *in vivo* studies on mice showed that PABA reduced UV damage.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In addition, it was shown to protect against skin tumors in rodents, as shown by a 1975 study ran by Dr.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] However, animal and *in vitro* studies in the early 1980s suggested PABA might increase the risk of cellular UV damage.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] On the basis of these studies, as well as problems with allergies and clothing discoloration, PABA fell out of favor as a sunscreen.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In 2008 it was banned as a sunscreen ingredient in the European Union and in 2019 the FDA proposed its limited use.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] However, water-insoluble PABA derivatives such as padimate O are currently used in some cosmetic products including mascara, concealer, and matte lipsticks.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] As of 2008, the advancement of new sunscreen is focused on developing a broad spectrum of active ingredients that provide consistent protection across all wavelengths, including UVA.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Researchers are considering the PABA–TiO2 Hybrid Nanostructures that result from the method of aqueous in situ synthesis with PABA and TiO2.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is largely nontoxic; the median lethal dose of PABA in dogs (oral) is 2 g/kg.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Allergic reactions, specifically allergic contact dermatitis and photocontact dermatitis, to PABA can occur.
[src:vitamin/4-aminobenzoic-acid] It is formed in the metabolism of certain ester-type local anesthetics, and many allergic reactions to local anesthetics are the result of reactions to PABA.
[src:vitamin/5-methylthioadenosine] The pervasive cofactor S-adenosyl methionine (SAM) is the precursor to 5′-methylthioadenosine.
[src:vitamin/5-methylthioadenosine] The sulfonium group in SAM can cleave in three ways, one involves loss of CH2CH2CH(NH3+)CO2−, generating the title compound.
[src:vitamin/5-methylthioadenosine] In 1912, an adenine nucleoside was isolated by Hunter *et al.* from yeast that were grown without phosphorus or sulfur.
[src:vitamin/5-methylthioadenosine] Later in 1925, that substance was shown by Levene and Sobotkal to be adenylthiomethylpentose.
[src:vitamin/5-methylthioadenosine] In 1936, Nakahara *et al.* did experiments on rats that suggested that vitamin L2 deficiency inhibits the ability of female rats for lactation.
[src:vitamin/5-methylthioadenosine] In 1942, they identified vitamin L2 to be adenylthiomethylpentose.
[src:vitamin/5-methylthioadenosine] Later studies by Folley *et al* (1942) refuted Nakahara's claims and demonstrated that L2 is not necessary for lactation and thus L2 is not considered a vitamin today.
[src:vitamin/5-methylthioadenosine] Hecht found in 1937 that the body temperature of rabbits, cats and guinea pigs were lowered by 1 to 2 degrees after he gave them adenylthiomethylpentose at a dose of 0.2 g/kg.
[src:vitamin/5-methylthioadenosine] Kühn *et al.* replicated this in guinea pigs in 1941.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] It is synthesized from lathosterol by the enzyme lathosterol oxidase (lathosterol 5-desaturase).
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] This is the next-to-last step of cholesterol biosynthesis.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Defective synthesis results in the human inherited disorder lathosterolosis resembling Smith–Lemli–Opitz syndrome.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Mice where this gene has been deleted lose the ability to increase vitamin D3 in the blood following UV exposure of the skin.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The skin consists of two primary layers: an inner layer, the dermis, comprising largely connective tissue, and an outer, thinner epidermis.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The thickness of the epidermis ranges from 0.04 mm to greater than 0.6 mm.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The epidermis comprises five *strata*; from outer to inner, they are the stratum corneum, stratum lucidum, stratum granulosum, stratum spinosum, and stratum basale.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The highest concentrations of 7-dehydrocholesterol are found in the epidermal layer of skin—specifically in the stratum basale and stratum spinosum.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The production of pre-vitamin D3 is, therefore, greatest in these two layers.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Synthesis of pre-vitamin D3 in the skin involves UVB radiation, which effectively penetrates only the epidermal layers of skin.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] 7-Dehydrocholesterol absorbs UV light most effectively at wavelengths between 295 and 300 nm and, thus, the production of vitamin D3 will occur primarily at those wavelengths.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The two most important factors that govern the generation of pre-vitamin D3 are the quantity (intensity) and quality (appropriate wavelength) of the UVB irradiation reaching the 7-dehydrocholesterol deep in the stratum basale and stratum spinosum.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Light-emitting diodes (LEDs) can be used to produce the radiation.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Another important consideration is the quantity of 7-dehydrocholesterol present in the skin.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Under normal circumstances, ample quantities of 7-dehydrocholesterol (about 25–50 μg/cm2 of skin) are available in the stratum spinosum and stratum basale of human skin to meet the body's vitamin D requirements.
[src:vitamin/7-dehydrocholesterol] 7-DHC insufficiency has been proposed as an alternate cause for Vitamin D deficiency.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The other essential nutrients are minerals, essential fatty acids, essential amino acids, and choline.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Some writers include choline as a vitamin.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Vitamins have diverse biochemical functions.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Vitamin A acts as a regulator of cell and tissue growth and differentiation.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Vitamin D provides a hormone-like function, regulating mineral metabolism for bones and other organs.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The B complex vitamins function as enzyme cofactors (coenzymes) or the precursors for them.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Vitamins C and E function as antioxidants.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Both deficient and excess intake of a vitamin can potentially cause clinically significant illness, although excess intake of water-soluble vitamins is less likely to do so.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] All the vitamins were discovered between 1910 and 1948.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Historically, when intake of vitamins from the diet was lacking, the results were vitamin deficiency diseases.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Then, starting in 1935, commercially produced tablets of yeast-extract vitamin B complex and semi-synthetic vitamin C became available.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] This was followed in the 1950s by the mass production and marketing of vitamin supplements, including multivitamins, to prevent vitamin deficiencies in the general population.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Governments have mandated the addition of some vitamins to staple foods such as flour or milk, referred to as food fortification, to prevent deficiencies.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Recommendations for folic acid supplementation during pregnancy reduced the risk of infant neural tube defects.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The term "vitamin" was derived from "vitamine", a portmanteau coined from "vital amine" in 1912 by the biochemist Casimir Funk and his friend Max Nierenstein, Reader of Biochemistry at Bristol University, while Funk was working at the Lister Institute of Preventive Medicine.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In 1920, Jack Cecil Drummond proposed that the final "e" be dropped to deemphasize the "amine" reference, hence "vitamin", after researchers began to suspect that not all "vitamines" (in particular, vitamin A) had an amine component.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The name "vitamin" soon became synonymous with Hopkins' "accessory factors".
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The value of eating certain foods to maintain health was recognized long before vitamins were identified in modern science.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The ancient Egyptians knew that feeding liver to a person may help with night blindness, an illness now known to be caused by a vitamin A deficiency.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The advance of ocean voyages during the Age of Discovery resulted in prolonged periods without access to fresh fruits and vegetables, and made illnesses from vitamin deficiency common among ships' crews.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In 1753, Lind published his *Treatise on the Scurvy*, which recommended using lemons and limes to avoid scurvy, which was adopted by the British Royal Navy.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] This led to the nickname *limey* for British sailors.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] However, during the 19th century, limes grown in the West Indies were substituted for lemons; these were subsequently found to be much lower in vitamin C.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] As a result, Arctic expeditions continued to be plagued by scurvy and other deficiency diseases.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In the early 20th century, when Robert Falcon Scott made his two expeditions to the Antarctic, the prevailing medical theory was that scurvy was caused by "tainted" canned food.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In 1881, Russian medical doctor Nikolai Lunin studied the effects of scurvy at the University of Tartu.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] He fed mice an artificial mixture of all the separate constituents of milk known at that time, namely the proteins, fats, carbohydrates, and salts.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The mice that received only the individual constituents died, while the mice fed by milk itself developed normally.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] He made a conclusion that "a natural food such as milk must therefore contain, besides these known principal ingredients, small quantities of unknown substances essential to life." However, his conclusions were rejected by his advisor, Gustav von Bunge.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] A similar result by Cornelis Adrianus Pekelharing appeared in Dutch medical journal *Nederlands Tijdschrift voor Geneeskunde* in 1905, but it was not widely reported.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In East Asia, where polished white rice was the common staple food of the middle class, beriberi resulting from lack of vitamin B1 was endemic.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In 1884, Takaki Kanehiro, a British-trained medical doctor of the Imperial Japanese Navy, observed that beriberi was endemic among low-ranking crew who often ate nothing but rice, but not among officers who consumed a Western-style diet.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] With the support of the Japanese navy, he experimented using crews of two battleships; one crew was fed only white rice, while the other was fed a diet of meat, fish, barley, rice, and beans.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The group that ate only white rice documented 161 crew members with beriberi and 25 deaths, while the latter group had only 14 cases of beriberi and no deaths.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] This convinced Takaki and the Japanese Navy that diet was the cause of beriberi, but they mistakenly believed that sufficient amounts of protein prevented it.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] That diseases could result from some dietary deficiencies was further investigated by Christiaan Eijkman, who in 1897 discovered that feeding unpolished rice instead of the polished variety to chickens helped to prevent a kind of polyneuritis that was the equivalent of beriberi.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The following year, Frederick Hopkins postulated that some foods contained "accessory factors" – in addition to proteins, carbohydrates, fats *etc.* – that are necessary for the functions of the human body.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In 1910, the first vitamin complex was isolated by Japanese scientist Umetaro Suzuki, who succeeded in extracting a water-soluble complex of micronutrients from rice bran and named it aberic acid (later *Orizanin*).
[src:vitamin/vitamin] He published this discovery in a Japanese scientific journal.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] When the article was translated into German, the translation failed to state that it was a newly discovered nutrient, a claim made in the original Japanese article, and hence his discovery failed to gain publicity.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Funk proposed the hypothesis that other diseases, such as rickets, pellagra, coeliac disease, and scurvy could also be cured by complexes like it.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The Nobel Prize for Chemistry for 1928 was awarded to Adolf Windaus "for his studies on the constitution of the sterols and their connection with vitamins", the first person to receive an award mentioning vitamins, even though it was not specifically about vitamin D.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for 1929 was awarded to Christiaan Eijkman and Frederick Gowland Hopkins for their contributions to the discovery of vitamins.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Thirty-five years earlier, Eijkman had observed that chickens fed polished white rice developed neurological symptoms similar to those observed in military sailors and soldiers fed a rice-based diet, and that the symptoms were reversed when the chickens were switched to whole-grain rice.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] He called this "the anti-beriberi factor", which was later identified as vitamin B1, thiamine.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In 1930, Paul Karrer elucidated the correct structure for beta-carotene, the main precursor of vitamin A, and identified other carotenoids.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Karrer and Norman Haworth confirmed Albert Szent-Györgyi's discovery of ascorbic acid and made significant contributions to the chemistry of flavins, which led to the identification of lactoflavin.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] For their investigations on carotenoids, flavins and vitamins A and B2, they both received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1937.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In 1931, Albert Szent-Györgyi and a fellow researcher Joseph Svirbely suspected that "hexuronic acid" was actually vitamin C, and gave a sample to Charles Glen King, who proved its ability to counter scurvy in his long-established guinea pig scorbutic assay.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In 1937, Szent-Györgyi was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his discovery.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In 1943, Edward Adelbert Doisy and Henrik Dam were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discovery of vitamin K and its chemical structure.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In 1938, Richard Kuhn was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his work on carotenoids and vitamins, specifically B2 and B6.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Five people have been awarded Nobel Prizes for direct and indirect studies of vitamin B12: George Whipple, George Minot and William P.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In 1967, George Wald, Ragnar Granit and Haldan Keffer Hartline were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology and Medicine "...for their discoveries concerning the primary physiological and chemical visual processes in the eye." Wald's contribution was discovering the role vitamin A had in the process.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Once discovered, vitamins were actively promoted in articles and advertisements in *McCall's*, *Good Housekeeping*, and other media outlets.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Marketers enthusiastically promoted cod-liver oil, a source of vitamin D, as "bottled sunshine", and bananas as a "natural vitality food".
[src:vitamin/vitamin] They promoted foods such as yeast cakes, a source of B vitamins, on the basis of scientifically determined nutritional value, rather than taste or appearance.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] It was thought appropriate to choose a name to dissociate nicotinic acid from nicotine, to avoid the perception that vitamins or niacin-rich food contains nicotine, or that cigarettes contain vitamins.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The resulting name *niacin* was derived from ***ni**cotinic **ac**id* + *vitam**in***.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Researchers also focused on the need to ensure adequate nutrition, especially to compensate for what was lost in the manufacture of processed foods.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Yoder is credited with first using the term *vitamania*, in 1942, to describe the appeal of relying on nutritional supplements rather than on obtaining vitamins from a varied diet of foods.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] The continuing preoccupation with a healthy lifestyle led to an obsessive consumption of vitamins and multi-vitamins, the beneficial effects of which are questionable.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] As one example, in the 1950s, the Wonder Bread company sponsored the Howdy Doody television show, with host Buffalo Bob Smith telling the audience, "Wonder Bread builds strong bodies 8 ways", referring to the number of added nutrients.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Vitamins are classified as either water-soluble or fat-soluble.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] In humans there are 13 vitamins: 4 fat-soluble (A, D, E, and K) and 9 water-soluble (8 B vitamins and vitamin C).
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Water-soluble vitamins dissolve easily in water and, in general, are readily excreted from the body, to the degree that urinary output is a strong predictor of vitamin consumption.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Because they are not as readily stored, more consistent intake is important.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Fat-soluble vitamins are absorbed through the gastrointestinal tract with the help of lipids (fats).
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Vitamins A and D can accumulate in the body, which can result in dangerous hypervitaminosis.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Fat-soluble vitamin deficiency due to malabsorption is of particular significance in cystic fibrosis.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Anti-vitamins are chemical compounds that inhibit the absorption or actions of vitamins.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] For example, avidin is a protein in raw egg whites that inhibits the absorption of biotin; it is deactivated by cooking.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Pyrithiamine, a synthetic compound, has a molecular structure similar to thiamine, vitamin B1, and inhibits the enzymes that use thiamine.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Each vitamin is typically used in multiple reactions, and therefore most have multiple functions.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Vitamins are essential for the normal growth and development of a multicellular organism.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Using the genetic blueprint inherited from its parents, a fetus develops from the nutrients it absorbs.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] It requires certain vitamins and minerals to be present at certain times.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] These nutrients facilitate the chemical reactions that produce among other things, skin, bone, and muscle.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] If there is serious deficiency in one or more of these nutrients, a child may develop a deficiency disease.
[src:vitamin/vitamin] Even minor deficiencies may cause permanent damage.
